        background-position: left top;
        background-repeat: no-repeat;
        width:49%;height:300px;
        margin:0px auto;
    "> </div> <!-- Flag profile -->
</code>

item.content:encoded:
Question:

When I type my php. The php works, but print this message:
<blockquote><em><span class="typ">Notice</span><span class="pun">:</span> <span class="typ">Use</span><span class="pln"> of </span><span class="kwd">undefined</span><span class="pln"> constant man</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln"> assumed </span><span class="str">'man'</span> <span class="pun">...</span></em></blockquote>
Why?

<!--more-->

Answer:

"Undefined" means "NO". Here's the code in simple way:
<code>class Man{
public $isAlive = true; public $male;
public function __construct($name,$male,$job,$nation)
{ $this -&gt; male = $male; }
public function ident(){
if (male==true) { return "Hello I am male." ; } }
}</code>
What's wrong is in last line<em>:</em>
<code>if (male==true) { return "Hello I am male." ; } </code>
The notice disappered when I type:
<code>if ($this-&gt;male==true) { return "Hello I am male." ; } </code>
Maybe PHP only know "$this-&gt;male" instead of "male"?
Maybe it is import to define "__construct" function?
But I still don't know why I need to define "__construct" function.
